Q1. Describe About the Software Composition Analysis (SCA) in Security Case Study (15 Marks)
Introduction

Software Composition Analysis (SCA) is a security process used to identify, analyze, and manage open-source and third-party software components used in an application.

Modern software is built using many libraries, frameworks, and packages. If any component contains vulnerabilities, attackers can exploit it.

SCA helps organizations detect these risks before deployment.

Why SCA is Important

Applications in banking and FinTech handle:

Customer data
Payments
Account information
Financial transactions

Using insecure components can cause:

Data breaches
Fraud
Compliance violations
Loss of trust
Security Case Study
Background

A FinTech company develops a wallet app using:

Open-source login library
Encryption package
Payment APIs

The development team uses old software components without checking security.

Problem

One third-party library has a known vulnerability.

An attacker exploits it and:

Accesses user accounts
Steals payment data
Performs fraud transactions
Impact
Financial loss
Data breach
Reputation damage
Compliance failure
Customer trust loss
Applying SCA

The company implements an SCA tool in development.

Steps
1. Scan Components

Detect all third-party libraries.

2. Identify Versions

Check installed versions.

3. Vulnerability Check

Compare with known CVE databases.

4. Risk Report

Show severity and affected components.

5. Suggest Fixes

Recommend updated secure versions.

6. Block Release

Stop deployment until issues are fixed.

Outcome
Vulnerable library replaced
Secure app release
Better compliance
Reduced attack risk
Improved customer trust
Benefits of SCA
Early vulnerability detection
Secure software supply chain
Better code quality
Supports DevSecOps
Saves cost and time
Popular SCA Tools
Snyk
OWASP Dependency-Check
Black Duck
Mend (WhiteSource)
Conclusion

SCA is an important modern security practice that protects applications by identifying risky third-party components before attackers can exploit them.

Q2 (a) Introduction of DevSecOps in FinTech (15 Marks)
Introduction

DevSecOps stands for:

Development
Security
Operations

It is a modern approach where security is included in every stage of software development.

Why Important in FinTech

FinTech systems handle:

Payments
Banking data
Customer identity
Sensitive transactions

So strong security is necessary.

Benefits of DevSecOps
Early bug detection
Secure releases
Faster updates
Better compliance
Reduced cyber risk
Example

Before launching a banking app update, automated security tests are performed.

Conclusion

DevSecOps helps FinTech companies deliver software quickly and securely.

Q2 (b) Explain the CI/CD
Introduction

CI/CD stands for:

Continuous Integration
Continuous Deployment / Delivery

It is an automated method of building, testing, and releasing software.

Continuous Integration (CI)

When developers add code:

Build starts automatically
Tests run automatically
Bugs found early
Continuous Deployment (CD)

After successful tests:

Software is deployed quickly
or
Prepared for release
Benefits
Faster development
Better software quality
Less manual work
Quick bug fixing
Example

A mobile wallet app receives regular updates safely.

Conclusion

CI/CD improves speed, quality, and efficiency of software delivery.

Q2 (c) Explain the SSDLC Introduction
Introduction

SSDLC stands for Secure Software Development Life Cycle.

It means security is included in every phase of software development.

Stages of SSDLC
1. Requirement Analysis

Define security needs.

2. Secure Design

Create secure architecture.

3. Secure Coding

Write safe code.

4. Security Testing

Use tools like:

SAST
DAST
SCA
5. Deployment

Release securely.

6. Maintenance

Monitor threats and update systems.

Importance
Protects customer data
Prevents attacks
Supports compliance
Builds secure apps
Conclusion

SSDLC ensures software remains secure from planning to maintenance
